<section class="section section--alt" id="qbo-int-square-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">What a Square&ndash;QuickBooks integration is, plainly.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Square is a point-of-sale and payments platform: it rings up sales, takes card payments, calculates sales tax, captures tips, and deposits the money to your bank. QuickBooks Online is your accounting system. A Square&ndash;QuickBooks integration is a connector app that sits between the two and brings your Square activity into QuickBooks automatically &mdash; sales, tips, sales tax collected, processing fees, refunds, and the deposits Square sends &mdash; so you&rsquo;re not re-keying the day&rsquo;s register into the books by hand.</p>
      <p>Here is the part that decides whether the books come out right. Square settles in <em>daily batches net of fees</em>. The deposit that hits your bank is not your sales total &mdash; it is one day&rsquo;s sales, plus the sales tax you collected, plus tips you&rsquo;re holding for staff, minus any refunds you issued, minus Square&rsquo;s processing fee, all netted into a single number. If that deposit is recorded as one lump sum of &ldquo;sales,&rdquo; three things go wrong at once: the <em>sales tax</em> you owe the state is buried inside revenue instead of sitting as a liability, the <em>tips</em> you&rsquo;re holding for employees are counted as your income, and the processing <em>fees</em> you paid never appear as an expense.</p>
      <p>Done well, the integration splits each batch the way it really happened: sales to income, sales tax to a tax-liability account, tips to a tips-payable liability, and fees to an expense account &mdash; and then you <a href="/quickbooks/online/features/reconciliation/">reconcile</a> the connected bank account to the actual Square batch deposits so the books tie to what Square paid out. We describe how the integration behaves and how to configure it accurately &mdash; we don&rsquo;t claim capabilities the apps don&rsquo;t have, and we&rsquo;re not affiliated with Square or Intuit.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

